1. Optimization for Removable Media (USB)
The script is engineered to maximize flash memory lifespan and ensure data persistence even in case of accidental disconnection:
-Write-Cycle Reduction: Through Session Buffering, the script avoids constantly rewriting the entire Database.7z archive. It writes only small buffer files, minimizing flash cell wear.
-Relative Pathing: The software automatically detects the USB drive letter via $BasePath. The hidden .data folder always resides on the portable media and never on the host PC.
-Zero-Footprint: No traces are left on the host computer. Necessary temporary files (7-Zip) are extracted to the systemâ€™s RAM/Temp and wiped immediately upon closure.
2. Database Anti-Corruption Protocol
The risk of â€œremoval corruptionâ€ (unplugging the USB during write) is mitigated by the sync logic:
-Deferred Synchronization: Since the merge into the main archive occurs only at startup, Database.7z remains in a read-only state most of the time, protecting historical logs.
3. High-Entropy Password Generator
The New-RandomPassword algorithm is tuned for 2026 security standards:
-Mandatory Enforcement: Guarantees 1 uppercase, 1 lowercase, 1 digit, and 1 special symbol.
-Indeterminism: Using Sort-Object {Get-Random} after selection ensures the password structure is never predictable, neutralizing pattern-based dictionary attacks.
4. Local Group Management (v1.1)
The 1.1 update introduces full support for managing local group memberships directly from the portable interface.
4.1 Overview
The system now allows administrators to:
-Add a user to any existing local group
-Remove a user from a local group
-Validate group existence before performing operations
-Prevent inconsistent states (e.g., removing a user who is not a member)
All operations are executed using secure PowerShell calls with elevated privileges.
4.2 Logging
Every groupâ€‘related action is now included in the encrypted log archive:
-Group assignment
-Group removal
-Validation errors
-Operation confirmations
Logs remain protected with AESâ€‘256 encryption and follow the same atomic buffering logic used for password operations.
4.3 Portable Behavior
Group operations follow the same safety model as password operations:
-No writes occur directly on the main archive during the session
-All changes are stored in session buffers
-Merging occurs only at application startup
This ensures maximum USB integrity and prevents corruption during unexpected removal.
  
Portable Specifications 2026
Storage: Hidden folder .data/ located on the USB root.
Temp: %TEMP%\Embedded7Zip_UserPwdMgr (with auto-cleanup).
Integrity: AES-256 encryption + Atomic buffering system.


